## 3. Step-by-Step Setup Commands

> All commands are run from **PowerShell** inside the project directory:
> `c:\xampp\htdocs\smart_attendance\`

---

### 3.1 Verify Python & pip

```powershell
python --version
pip --version
```

**Expected output:**
```
Python 3.10.3
pip 22.0.4 from C:\Program Files\Python310\lib\site-packages\pip (python 3.10)
```

---

### 3.2 Check Virtual Environment

The project already contained a `venv/` folder. Verify it exists and what is installed:

```powershell
.\venv\Scripts\python.exe --version
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe list
```

**Output found (bare venv — only these were present):**
```
Package    Version
---------- -------
pip        26.0.1
setuptools 58.1.0
```

> [!NOTE]
> If you don't have a `venv/` folder yet, create one first:
> ```powershell
> python -m venv venv
> ```

---

### 3.3 Identify Disk Space Issue

Before installing, we checked available disk space because the first install attempt failed:

```powershell
Get-PSDrive C | Select-Object Used, Free
Get-PSDrive D | Select-Object Used, Free
```

**Output:**
```
C: — Used: 127 GB   Free: ~62 MB   ← CRITICALLY LOW
D: — Used: 7 GB     Free: ~115 GB  ← Plenty of space
```

> [!CAUTION]
> **C: drive had only ~62 MB free.** pip's temp and cache directories defaulted to `%TEMP%` on C:, causing the first install to fail with:
> `ERROR: Could not install packages due to an OSError: [Errno 28] No space left on device`
>
> The fix: redirect pip's cache and temp directories to D: drive for all subsequent installs.

---

### 3.4 Install Core Dependencies

**First attempt — FAILED (disk space):**
```powershell
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install "flask>=2.3,<4.0" "opencv-python>=4.8,<5.0" "numpy>=1.24,<2.0" "pandas>=2.0,<3.0" "mysql-connector-python>=8.1,<9.0" "bcrypt>=4.0,<5.0" "Pillow>=10.0,<11.0"
```

**Error received:**
```
ERROR: Could not install packages due to an OSError: [Errno 28] No space left on device
```

**Second attempt — redirected to D: drive — SUCCEEDED:**
```powershell
$env:TEMP="D:\pip_tmp"
$env:TMP="D:\pip_tmp"
New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force "D:\pip_tmp"

.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install --cache-dir "D:\pip_cache" `
    "flask>=2.3,<4.0" `
    "opencv-python>=4.8,<5.0" `
    "numpy>=1.24,<2.0" `
    "pandas>=2.0,<3.0" `
    "mysql-connector-python>=8.1,<9.0" `
    "bcrypt>=4.0,<5.0" `
    "Pillow>=10.0,<11.0"
```

**Packages successfully installed (with exact versions):**

| Package | Version | Purpose |
|---------|---------|---------|
| flask | 3.1.3 | Web framework |
| opencv-python | 4.11.0.86 | Webcam / image processing |
| numpy | 1.26.4 | Numerical arrays (face encoding math) |
| pandas | 2.3.3 | Data handling |
| mysql-connector-python | 8.4.0 | MySQL database driver |
| bcrypt | 4.3.0 | Password hashing |
| Pillow (PIL) | 10.4.0 | Image file handling |
| werkzeug | 3.1.8 | Flask dependency (WSGI) |
| jinja2 | 3.1.6 | Flask dependency (HTML templates) |
| click | 8.3.2 | Flask dependency (CLI) |
| itsdangerous | 2.2.0 | Flask dependency (session signing) |
| blinker | 1.9.0 | Flask dependency (signals) |
| colorama | 0.4.6 | Colored terminal output (Windows) |
| python-dateutil | 2.9.0.post0 | Date parsing (pandas dependency) |
| pytz | 2026.1.post1 | Timezone support |
| tzdata | 2026.1 | Timezone database |
| six | 1.17.0 | Python 2/3 compatibility shim |
| markupsafe | 3.0.3 | Jinja2 dependency |

---

### 3.5 Install dlib (The Tricky One)

`face_recognition` depends on `dlib`, which **requires C++ compilation on Windows** using CMake and Visual Studio Build Tools. This is the most error-prone step on Windows.

**Attempt — pip tries to build dlib from source — FAILED:**
```powershell
$env:TEMP="D:\pip_tmp"; $env:TMP="D:\pip_tmp"
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install --cache-dir "D:\pip_cache" "face-recognition>=1.3,<2.0"
```

**Error received (after ~5 minutes of downloading and attempting to compile):**
```
subprocess.CalledProcessError: Command '['cmake', 'D:\\pip_tmp\\pip-install-...\\dlib_...\\tools\\python',
'-DCMAKE_LIBRARY_OUTPUT_DIRECTORY=...', '-DPYTHON_EXECUTABLE=...', '-A', 'x64']'
returned non-zero exit status 1.

ERROR: Failed building wheel for dlib
Failed to build installable wheels for some pyproject.toml based projects: dlib
```

**Root cause:** CMake and/or Visual Studio C++ Build Tools were not installed or not on the PATH.

---

#### The Fix — Use a pre-built dlib wheel

Instead of compiling dlib from source, download a community-maintained pre-compiled `.whl` binary from GitHub:

> **Repository:** https://github.com/z-mahmud22/Dlib_Windows_Python3.x

**Step 1 — Download the wheel for Python 3.10 win_amd64 to D: drive:**
```powershell
Invoke-WebRequest `
  -Uri "https://github.com/z-mahmud22/Dlib_Windows_Python3.x/raw/refs/heads/main/dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl" `
  -OutFile "D:\dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl" `
  -UseBasicParsing
```

**Step 2 — Install the downloaded wheel:**
```powershell
$env:TEMP="D:\pip_tmp"; $env:TMP="D:\pip_tmp"
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install --cache-dir "D:\pip_cache" "D:\dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl"
```

**Expected output:**
```
Processing D:\dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl
Installing collected packages: dlib
Successfully installed dlib-19.22.99
```

> [!TIP]
> **Choosing the right wheel for other Python versions:**
>
> Filename format: `dlib-{version}-cp{pyver}-cp{pyver}-win_amd64.whl`
>
> | Your Python | Wheel filename |
> |-------------|----------------|
> | Python 3.8  | `dlib-19.22.99-cp38-cp38-win_amd64.whl` |
> | Python 3.9  | `dlib-19.22.99-cp39-cp39-win_amd64.whl` |
> | Python 3.10 | `dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl` |
> | Python 3.11 | `dlib-19.22.99-cp311-cp311-win_amd64.whl` |
>
> Browse all available wheels: https://github.com/z-mahmud22/Dlib_Windows_Python3.x

---

### 3.6 Install face_recognition

With dlib already installed, `face_recognition` installs cleanly:

```powershell
$env:TEMP="D:\pip_tmp"; $env:TMP="D:\pip_tmp"
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install --cache-dir "D:\pip_cache" "face-recognition>=1.3,<2.0"
```

**Expected output:**
```
Collecting face-recognition-models>=0.3.0
  Downloading face_recognition_models-0.3.0-py2.py3-none-any.whl (100.1 MB)
...
Successfully installed face-recognition-1.3.0 face-recognition-models-0.3.0
```

> [!NOTE]
> `face-recognition-models` is ~100 MB — it contains the HOG descriptor model and deep learning landmark detection files. Download time depends on your internet speed.

