## 4. Errors Encountered & How They Were Fixed

### Error 1 — `[Errno 28] No space left on device`

| Field | Detail |
|-------|--------|
| **When** | First `pip install` attempt |
| **Cause** | C: drive had only ~62 MB free. pip writes download cache and build temp files to `%TEMP%` which defaults to C: |
| **Full error** | `ERROR: Could not install packages due to an OSError: [Errno 28] No space left on device` |
| **Fix** | Redirect TEMP, TMP and pip cache to D: drive before every install |

```powershell
# Solution — add these lines before any pip install:
$env:TEMP="D:\pip_tmp"
$env:TMP="D:\pip_tmp"
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install --cache-dir "D:\pip_cache" <packages>
```

---

### Error 2 — dlib CMake / C++ Build Failure

| Field | Detail |
|-------|--------|
| **When** | `pip install face-recognition` (which auto-pulls dlib) |
| **Cause** | dlib has no pre-built binary wheel on PyPI for Windows. It must be compiled from C++ source, which requires CMake and Visual Studio Build Tools — neither was installed |
| **Full error** | `subprocess.CalledProcessError: Command '['cmake', ...]' returned non-zero exit status 1` then `ERROR: Failed building wheel for dlib` |
| **Fix** | Download a community pre-built `.whl` file from GitHub and install it directly, bypassing compilation entirely |

```powershell
# Download pre-built dlib (Python 3.10, Windows 64-bit)
Invoke-WebRequest `
  -Uri "https://github.com/z-mahmud22/Dlib_Windows_Python3.x/raw/refs/heads/main/dlib-19.22.99-cp310-cp310-win_amd64.whl" `
  -OutFile "D:\dlib.whl" -UseBasicParsing

# Install the wheel directly
.\venv\Scripts\pip.exe install "D:\dlib.whl"
```

---

### Error 3 — Login Fails: "Invalid username or password"

| Field | Detail |
|-------|--------|
| **When** | First browser login attempt after database import |
| **Cause** | bcrypt hashes include a random salt — the hash in `schema.sql` was generated on a different machine and does not match `admin123` when verified on this machine |
| **Symptom** | Login page shows "Invalid username or password" even though credentials are correct |
| **Fix** | Re-generate the bcrypt hash using the current Python environment and update the database row directly via Python (see Section 3.8) |

---

### Error 4 — Dollar Signs Mangled by PowerShell

| Field | Detail |
|-------|--------|
| **When** | Attempted to update the password hash via `mysql.exe` CLI directly from PowerShell |
| **Cause** | PowerShell treats `$` as variable interpolation inside double-quoted strings. The bcrypt hash `$2b$12$lVefo...` got corrupted — the `$2b$12$` part was interpreted as variables and stripped out |
| **Symptom** | Stored hash appeared truncated in the database (e.g., showed `\\/Rwg7gg...` instead of the full hash) |
| **Fix** | Used Python with `mysql-connector-python` parameterised queries instead of shell string interpolation — the hash is passed as a Python bytes/string object with no shell involvement |

```python
# WRONG — do not do this in PowerShell, $ gets mangled:
# mysql.exe ... "UPDATE admin_users SET password_hash = '$2b$12$...' ..."

# CORRECT — parameterised query, no shell interpolation:
cur.execute('UPDATE admin_users SET password_hash = %s WHERE username = %s', (hash_value, 'admin'))
```

